git-svn-id: https://mary.opendfki.de/repos/trunk@351 953a6561-930b-0410-b2a6-db37d1b2ae63

More informative exceptions: Replaced all "throw new Error(...)"
with context-specific Exceptions. Errors should only be used in
the very rare case that the program execution (Java itself) is
going totally wrong. For our tests of program logic, we should
never use Errors, but Exceptions which are as specific as possible
and which retain the stack trace. Either we simply choose not to catch
exceptions from methods we call; or if we catch them and
*add them as a cause* to the new exception we throw.

For example, using code like the following helps 
to understand what went wrong:

try {
...
} catch (IOException ioe) {
   IOException newIOE = new IOException("Problem dumping carts");
   newIOE.initCause(ioe);
   throw newIOE;
}

